					<td>
					<div class="header4">SourceForge Initiative</div>
					
					&nbsp;<br>
					Many folks in the know are just waiting for the release of JSR 168 and its various implementations. Others who might benefit from the technology remain oblivious. To help get the word out, Plumtree, working with Documentum, BEA, and Sun, set up a project called the Portlet Open Source Trading Site (POST) (http://portlet-opensrc.sourceforge.net/) hosted on SourceForge.net (SF.net), where lots of techie people are known to mix and mingle. In fact, SF.net's About page says it is considered the "world's largest open source software development web site, providing free hosting to tens of thousands of projects."<br> 
							
					&nbsp;<br>		
					As part of SF.net, POST aims to give developers a central location for learning about, collaborating on, and building portlets based on the new JSR 168 and WSRP specifications. BEA and Plumtree have posted sample code in an effort to kick off development in an open manner. Shane Pearson of BEA says, "We see it as another forum to push the JSR 168 specification and provide another avenue of information about how to implement."<br> 
					
					&nbsp;<br>
					<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" align="left" width="93">
						<tr>
						<td width="80"></td>
						<td width="19"><img src="/images/common/trans.gif" alt="" width="8" height="1" border="0"></td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
						<td><img src="/images/press/ross_fubini.jpg" width="80" height="80" border="0" alt="Ross Fubini"></td>
						<td><img src="/images/common/trans.gif" alt="" width="13" height="14" border="0"></td>
